# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: idor-prevention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:idor-prevention/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Authorization is closely related to access control, which is what enforces the authorization policy by deciding whether access requests to resources from (authenticated) consumers shall be approved (granted) or disapproved (rejected).
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Authorization should not be confused with authentication, which is the process of verifying someone's identity.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Hence, access control in computer systems and networks relies on access authorization specified during configuration.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Authorization is the responsibility of an authority, such as a department manager, within the application domain, but is often delegated to a custodian such as a system administrator.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Authorizations are expressed as access policies in some types of "policy definition application", e.g. in the form of an access control list or a capability, or a policy administration point e.g.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Broken authorization is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] "Anonymous consumers" or "guests", are consumers that have not been required to authenticate.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] On a distributed system, it is often desirable to grant access without requiring a unique identity.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Familiar examples of access tokens include keys, certificates and tickets: they grant access without proving identity.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] A widely used framework for authorizing applications is OAuth 2.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] It provides a standardized way for third-party applications to obtain limited access to a user's resources without exposing their credentials.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] In modern systems, a widely used model for authorization is role-based access control (RBAC) where authorization is defined by granting subjects one or more roles, and then checking that the resource being accessed has been assigned at least one of those roles.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] However, with the rise of social media, Relationship-based access control is gaining more prominence.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Even when access is controlled through a combination of authentication and access control lists, the problems of maintaining the authorization data is not trivial, and often represents as much administrative burden as managing authentication credentials.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] It is often necessary to change or remove a user's authorization: this is done by changing or deleting the corresponding access rules on the system.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] Using atomic authorization is an alternative to per-system authorization management, where a trusted third party securely distributes authorization information.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] In public policy, authorization is a feature of trusted systems used for security or social control.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] In banking, an authorization is a hold placed on a customer's account when a purchase is made using a debit card or credit card.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] In publishing, sometimes public lectures and other freely available texts are published without the approval of the author.
[src:idor-prevention/authorization] An example is the 2002 *'The Theory of Everything: The Origin and Fate of the Universe'*, which was collected from Stephen Hawking's lectures and published without his permission as per copyright law.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] An **identifier** is a name that identifies (that is, labels the identity of) either a unique class of objects or a unique instance of such objects; the class or instance may be an idea, person, physical countable object (or class thereof), or physical noncountable substance (or class thereof).
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] The abbreviation "**ID**" may refer to identity, identification (the process of identifying), or an identifier (that is, an instance of identification).
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] An identifier may be a word, number, letter, symbol, or any combination of those.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] If the identifier follows an encoding system—wherein parts of the identifier *stand for* [represent] ideas or longer names—it is often referred to as a ***code*** or ***ID code***.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Identifiers that do not follow any encoding scheme are often said to be ***arbitrary IDs*** as they have no greater meaning.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] A *unique identifier* (UID) is an identifier that refers to *only one instance*—only one particular object in the universe.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] A part number is an identifier, but it is not a *unique* identifier—for that, a serial number would be needed, to identify *each instance* of the part design.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] For example, the *identifier* "Model T" identifies the class (or model) of automobiles that Ford's Model T comprises; whereas the *unique identifier* "Model T Serial Number 159,862" identifies one specific member of that class—that is, one particular Model T car, owned by one specific person.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] In metadata, an identifier is a language-independent label, sign or token that uniquely identifies an object within an identification scheme.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] The suffix "identifier" is also used as a representation term when naming a data element.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] ID codes may inherently carry metadata along with them.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Arbitrary identifiers might lack metadata.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] For example, if a food package just says 100054678214, its ID may not tell anything except identity—no date, manufacturer name, production sequence rank, or inspector number.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] In some cases, arbitrary identifiers such as sequential serial numbers leak information (i.e. the German tank problem).
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Opaque identifiers—identifiers designed to avoid leaking even that small amount of information—include "really opaque pointers" and Version 4 UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] In computer science, identifiers (IDs) are lexical tokens that name entities.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Identifiers are used extensively in virtually all information processing systems.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Identifying entities makes it possible to refer to them, which is essential for any kind of symbolic processing.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] In computer languages, identifiers are tokens (also called symbols) which name language entities.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Some of the kinds of entities an identifier might denote include variables, types, labels, subroutines, and packages.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] A resource may carry multiple identifiers.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] The inverse is also possible, where multiple resources are represented with the same identifier (discussed below).
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Many codes and nomenclatural systems originate within a small namespace.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Over the years, some of them bleed into larger namespaces (as people interact in ways they formerly had not, e.g., cross-border trade, scientific collaboration, military alliance, and general cultural interconnection or assimilation).
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] When such dissemination happens, the limitations of the original naming convention, which had formerly been latent and moot, become painfully apparent, often necessitating retronymy, synonymity, translation/transcoding, and so on.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Such limitations generally accompany the shift away from the original context to the broader one.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] Within computer science, this problem is called naming collision.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] The story of the origination and expansion of the CODEN system provides a good case example in a recent-decades, technical-nomenclature context.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] The capitalization variations seen with specific designators reveals an instance of this problem occurring in natural languages, where the proper noun/common noun distinction (and its complications) must be dealt with.
[src:idor-prevention/identifier] A universe in which every object had a UID would not need any namespaces, which is to say that it would constitute one gigantic namespace; but human minds could never keep track of, or semantically interrelate, so many UIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR) is a vulnerability that arises when attackers can access or modify objects by manipulating identifiers used in a web application's URLs or parameters.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] It occurs due to missing access control checks, which fail to verify whether a user should be allowed to access specific data.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] A **reference** to that object in the form of an ID, UUID, account number, token or slug.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] A **missing object-level authorization check** that allows a user to access or manipulate an object they should not be able to access.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] The 123 in the URL is a direct reference to the user's record in the database, often represented by the primary key.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] If an attacker changes this number to 124 and gains access to another user's information, the application is vulnerable to Insecure Direct Object Reference.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] This happens because the app didn't properly check if the user had permission to view data for user 124 before displaying it.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] In this example, the application allows users to update their profiles by submitting a form with the user ID in a hidden field.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] If the app doesn't perform proper access control on the server-side, attackers can manipulate the "user_id" field to modify profiles of other users without authorization.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] IDORs however are not limited to user profiles and sequential IDs.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] In this example, the filename acts as the object reference.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] and gains access to a document belonging to another user, the application is vulnerable to IDOR.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Object references are not limited to numeric identifiers and may include filenames, account numbers, tokens, or other values.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] In some cases, using more complex identifiers like GUIDs can make it practically impossible for attackers to guess valid values.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] However, even with complex identifiers, access control checks are essential.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] If attackers obtain URLs for unauthorized objects, the application should still block their access attempts.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] When testing for IDOR vulnerabilities, it is useful to create multiple user accounts with different authorization scopes.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] This allows developers and testers to verify that object-level authorization checks are consistently enforced.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Create objects owned by each user (documents, support tickets, invoices, etc.).
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Authenticate as User A and attempt to access User B's objects by modifying object references in requests.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Verify that the application denies unauthorized access regardless of whether the object identifier is predictable or unguessable.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] This verification should be performed for all operations involving object references, including read, create, update, delete, export, and administrative actions.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] To mitigate IDOR, implement access control checks for each object that users try to access.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Web frameworks often provide ways to facilitate this.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Additionally, use complex identifiers as a defense-in-depth measure, but remember that access control is crucial even with these identifiers.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Avoid exposing identifiers in URLs and POST bodies if possible.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Instead, determine the currently authenticated user from session information.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] When using multi-step flows, pass identifiers in the session to prevent tampering.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] When looking up objects based on primary keys, use datasets that users have access to.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Verify the user's permission every time an access attempt is made.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Implement this structurally using the recommended approach for your web framework.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] As an additional defense-in-depth measure, replace enumerable numeric identifiers with more complex, random identifiers.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] You can achieve this by adding a column with random strings in the database table and using those strings in the URLs instead of numeric primary keys.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Another option is to use UUIDs or other long random values as primary keys.
[src:idor-prevention/insecure-direct-object-reference-prevention-cheat-sheet] Avoid encrypting identifiers as it can be challenging to do so securely.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] A **universally unique identifier** (**UUID**) is a 128-bit number used to identify information in computer systems.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The term **globally unique identifier** (**GUID**) is also used, typically in software created by Microsoft.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] When generated according to the standards, UUIDs are, for practical purposes, unique.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Their uniqueness does not depend on a central registration authority or coordination between the parties generating them, unlike most other numbering schemes.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] While the probability that a UUID will be duplicated is not zero, it is close enough to zero to be negligible.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, anyone can create large numbers of UUIDs and use them as identifiers with near certainty that they do not duplicate UUIDs that have been, or will be, created by others, with the only coordination required to achieve uniqueness being conformance with the UUID standards.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Information labeled with UUIDs by independent parties can therefore coexist in the same databases or channels, with a negligible probability of duplication.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Adoption of UUIDs is widespread, with many computing platforms providing support for generating them and for parsing their textual representation.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Apollo Computer used UUIDs in the Network Computing System (NCS), launched in 1987, with a design inspired by the 64-bit unique identifiers of Domain/OS, an earlier Apollo operating system.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Microsoft Windows platforms adopted the NCS (and later, the DCE) design as "Globally Unique Identifiers" (GUIDs) in the early nineties.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Somewhat later, the Open Software Foundation (OSF) used UUIDs in its Distributed Computing Environment (DCE), with a design partly based on the NCS UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This was documented in the DCE 1.1 RPC specification in 1996, and in the DCE 1.1 Authentication and Security Services specification, published in 1997.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] ISO/IEC documented the DCE design in 1996, in ISO/IEC 11578:1996 "Information technology – Open Systems Interconnection – Remote Procedure Call".
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In July 2005, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) published the Standards-Track RFC 4122., which also registered a URN namespace for UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The ITU had meanwhile also standardized UUIDs, based on the previous standards and early versions of RFC 4122, in ITU-T Rec.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This was technically equivalent to RFC 4122.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The current IETF specification is RFC 9562, a Proposed Standard published in May 2024.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This defined three new UUID versions (6–8) of the DCE variant.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The UUIDs currently in use are the DCE/IETF design, with provision for backwards compatibility with "legacy" Apollo NCS UUIDs and Microsoft GUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The authors of RFC 4122 were Paul Leach, Michael Mealling, and Rich Salz, and the authors of the initial 1997 Internet Draft were Leach and Salz.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Leach had been the Architect of Domain/OS, had continued at Apollo as a designer of NCS, and then, as a Microsoft Distinguished Architect, contributed to the design of OLE/COM/DCOM, carrying the concept of UUIDs to that project.Leach was also one of the authors of RFC 9562.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Salz was a member of the DCE team at the Open Software Foundation.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Apollo had merged in 1989 with Hewlett-Packard, a founding member of the OSF.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Former NCS team-members, having become HP employees, brought UUIDs to OSF DCE.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Mealling was a prominent IETF member, holding a seat on the Internet Engineering Steering Group, and was heavily involved in IETF work on URNs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 brought all these strands together.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The meaning of the bits is determined by the *variant*, of which three are defined.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Of these, the most common is variant 1, with the other variants being for backwards compatibility with previous formats or for future definition.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Variants 1 and 2 have "versions", which further define the interpretation of the UUID.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The *variant* field is in a variable number of the most-significant bits of the ninth byte.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The OSF DCE and Microsoft COM/DCOM variants (1 & 2, respectively) have *versions*, indicated by the value of the high four bits of the seventh byte of the UUID.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In textual representations of the UUID, this is the hex digit after the second hyphen.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Variant 0 Apollo NCS UUIDs do not have versions, being sub-typed via "address families" rather than versions.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562, which defined versions 6, 7, and 8 stated that variants other than the OSF DCE variant 1 were "out of scope" of the RFC, leaving it to Microsoft to define new versions for variant 2.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] However, versions 1 through 5, standardized in RFC 4122, are the same in the Microsoft variant, except for byte-ordering.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Version 1 concatenates the 48-bit MAC address of the "node" (that is, the computer generating the UUID), with a 60-bit timestamp.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] On systems with 64-bit EUI-64 "MAC addresses", the least significant 48 bits are used.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] A 48-bit random number may also be used.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The timestamp is the number of 100-nanosecond intervals since midnight 15 October 1582 Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), the date on which the Gregorian calendar was first adopted.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 states that the time value rolls over in A.D.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] 3409,depending on the algorithm used, which implies that the 60-bit timestamp is a signed quantity.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] However some software, such as the libuuid library, treats the timestamp as unsigned, putting the rollover time in A.D.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] A 13-bit or 14-bit "uniquifying" clock sequence extends the timestamp in order to handle cases where the processor clock does not advance fast enough, or where there are multiple processors and UUID generators per node.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] When UUIDs are generated faster than the system clock can advance, the lower bits of the timestamp and the clock sequence can be incremented to simulate greater precision and ensure uniqueness.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] With each version-1 UUID corresponding to a single point in space (the node) and time (intervals and clock sequence), the chance of two properly generated version-1 UUIDs being unintentionally the same is practically nil.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Since the time and clock sequence total 74 bits, 274 (1.8×1022, or 18 sextillion) version-1 UUIDs can be generated per node ID, at a maximal average rate of 163 billion per second per node ID.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Version 6 is the same as version 1 except for the order of the timestamp bits.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In version 6, timestamp bits are ordered from most significant to least significant.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This allows systems to sort version-6 UUIDs in order of creation simply by sorting them lexically.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] By reinstating the original NCS hi-lo byte order of the timestamp to enable sortability, version 6 is even more similar to "legacy" variant 0 NCS UUIDs than version 1.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFCs 4122 and 9562 reserve version 2 for "DCE security" UUIDs; but do not provide any details.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Many UUID implementations and libraries omit version 2.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] However, the specification of version-2 UUIDs is provided by the DCE 1.1 Authentication and Security Services specification.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Version-2 UUIDs are similar to version 1, except that the least significant 8 bits of the clock sequence are replaced by a "local domain" number, and the least significant 32 bits of the 60-bit Gregorian timestamp are replaced by an integer identifier meaningful within the specified local domain.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] On POSIX systems, local-domain numbers 0 and 1 are for user ids (UIDs) and group ids (GIDs) respectively, and other local-domain numbers are site-defined.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] On non-POSIX systems, all local domain numbers are site-defined.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, version-2 UUIDs are a way to combine a 32-bit local, node-scoped identifier of a specified 8-bit type ("domain") with the identifier of the node and a Gregorian-origin timestamp, transforming the node-scoped identifier into one that is universally unique.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The tradeoff is that the timestamp is low-res in comparison to the timestamps in version 1, ticking only once once every 429.49 seconds, a little more than 7 minutes, quite different from the 100 nanosecond ticks in version 1.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Version-3 and version-5 UUIDs are generated by hashing a namespace identifier and name.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Version 3 uses MD5 as the hashing algorithm, and version 5 uses SHA-1.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This is useful when systems need deterministically to generate the same UUID based on a set of other names or identifiers, without coordination.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The namespace identifier is itself a UUID.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC provides constant UUIDs to represent the namespaces for URLs, fully qualified domain names, object identifiers, and X.500 distinguished names; but any desired UUID may be used as a namespace designator.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] There is an IANA registry for additional namespace ids.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] To determine the version-3 UUID corresponding to a given namespace and name, the UUID of the namespace is transformed to a string of bytes, concatenated with the input name, then hashed with MD5, yielding 128 bits.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Then six or seven bits are replaced by fixed values, the four-bit version (e.g.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] 00112 for version 3), and the two- or three-bit UUID "variant" (e.g.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] 102 indicating an RFC 9562 UUIDs, or 1102 indicating a legacy Microsoft GUID).
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Since 6 or 7 bits are thus predetermined, only 121 or 122 bits contribute to the uniqueness of the UUID.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Version-5 UUIDs are similar, but SHA-1 is used instead of MD5.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Since SHA-1 generates 160-bit digests, the digest is truncated to 128 bits before the version and variant bits are replaced.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Version-3 and version-5 UUIDs have the property that, given the version, the same namespace and name will map to the same UUID.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] However, neither the namespace nor name can be determined from the UUID, even if one of them is specified, except by brute-force search.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 recommends version 5 (SHA-1) over version 3 (MD5).
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This is because it is believed that MD5 is more prone to collisions than SHA-1, though MD5 is somewhat faster.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC warns against use of UUIDs of any version as security capabilities.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] As in other UUIDs, four bits are used to indicate version 4, and two or three bits to indicate the variant (102 or 1102 for variants 1 and 2 respectively).
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, for variant 1 (that is, most UUIDs) a random version-4 UUID will have six predetermined variant and version bits, leaving 122 bits for the randomly generated part, for a total of 2122, or 5.3×1036 (5.3 undecillion) possible version-4, variant-1 UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] There are half as many possible version-4, variant 2 UUIDs (legacy GUIDs) because there is one less random bit available, three bits being consumed for the variant.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Version-7 UUIDs are intended as monotonically ascending, creation-time-ordered, lexically sortable keys in large databases and distributed systems, contributing to locality and performance.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] With version 7 as database keys, "new" records are inserted at the logical end of the key sequence, and records which are close in time are near each other in the key sequence.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This contrasts with the random version 4, which when used as database keys, are evenly and randomly dispersed across the key sequence, even when the underlying records are close in time, negatively affecting performance in many types of databases.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The 48-bit timestamps may be altered, fuzzed, or smeared for the sake of monotonicity and privacy, and it is explicitly stated that there is no requirement about how close a timestamp needs to be to the actual (Unix) time.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] But the intent is clear that the timestamps should be monontonic and approximate Unix time, and the RFC states that custom UUID version 8 should be used for timestamp-based designs that are not Unix time.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Unlike some other UUID versions, version-7 UUIDs do not incorporate MAC addresses, and can steer clear of the privacy issues associated with them.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In a custom UUID, the version is `8`, and the variant bits must be `10`, totaling 6 bits.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The remaining 122 bits are not specified.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] According to the RFC, version-8 UUIDs are intended for experimental and vendor-specific use cases.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC suggests, for example, that this version might be used for a name/hash-based identifier generated with a newer hashing function than those specified for UUID versions 3 (MD5) and 5 (SHA-1).
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC also suggests that version 8 can be used for timestamp-based UUID designs that do not fit within versions 6 or 7, such as a different epoch.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] But version 8 is not restricted to such scenarios.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In essence, version-8 UUIDs are 122 opaque bits, combined with six version and variant bits, allowing them to be separated from other UUID forms.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Unlike other versions, the RFC does not mandate a specific bit layout or generation algorithm, and they are not to be assumed to be unique.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In addition, as with other UUID versions, there is no concept of version subtypes.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The uniqueness of the UUIDs based on network-card MAC addresses also depends on network-card manufacturers properly assigning unique MAC addresses to their cards which, like other manufacturing processes, is subject to error.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] MAC addresses also may come from sources other than network cards.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] For example, virtual machines receive a MAC address from a range that is configurable in the hypervisor, and some operating systems permit the end user to customise the MAC address, notably OpenWrt.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] When a device has an EUI-64 64-bit "MAC address", using the least significant 48 bits of it, as recommended by the RFC, may result in the node ID part of the UUID being duplicated.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, node IDs based on MAC addresses may not be globally unique.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Usage of the node's network card MAC address for the node ID does often mean that version-1, -2, and -6 UUIDs can be tracked back to the computer that created them.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Such UUIDs can be used to infer what kind of hardware is being used to generate the UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Documents can sometimes be traced to the computers where they were created or edited through UUIDs embedded into them by word processing software.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This privacy hole was used when locating the creator of the Melissa virus.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562 does allow the MAC address in a version-1, -2 or -6 UUID to be replaced by a random 48-bit node ID, either because the node does not have a MAC address, or because it is not desirable to include it.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In that case, the RFC requires that the least significant bit of the first octet of the node ID should be set to 1.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This corresponds to the multicast bit in MAC addresses, and setting it serves to differentiate UUIDs where the node ID is randomly generated from UUIDs based on MAC addresses from network cards, which typically have unicast MAC addresses.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Versions 1, 2, 6, and 7 are based on, and expose, the time when the UUID was generated, which often corresponds to the creation of a record, or an historical event.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] If associated with people or their activity, it may be possible to infer a person's age or the precise time of their activities from UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] It may be possible to determine from time-based monotonically-ascending UUIDs when a system went live, or what objects in a system are new or recently updated.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] If the identified objects represent product orders or user sign-ups, for example, it may be possible to determine user growth or sales volume over time from the UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, time-based UUIDs, if publicly visible, may leak personal or business information, raise privacy concerns, and facilitate unwanted data mining.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Concerning the time-ordering and sortability of UUIDs, version 1 and 2 start "in the middle" with the 32 low bits of the timestamp.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] These two versions, along with 3–5 and 8, do not sort lexically into time order.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The role of the timestamp in these UUID versions was not to make UUIDs readily orderable in time but rather to achieve universal uniqueness by fixing the generation in space and time.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Versions 6 and 7 prioritize the timestamp's role in database indexing, allowing for lexical sorting of records into chronological order.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] However, RFC 9562 provides significant implementation flexibility for version 7, defining a general framework rather than a rigid bit-layout for optional sub-millisecond timestamp precision, counters, and randomness.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The specification allows the 48-bit Unix timestamp to be adjusted or "fuzzed" to maintain monotonicity (ensuring IDs created in rapid succession always increase) or to enhance privacy.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Because the RFC does not define a strict maximum deviation from actual Unix time, different implementations may vary in how they balance chronological accuracy against these other requirements.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Consequently, the lexical sortability of versions 6 and 7 UUIDs is most consistent when generated by the same library or system.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Mixing UUIDs from different sources, or interleaving different versions and variants in a single database, can degrade the time-ordering and index locality that these versions were designed to provide.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562 does not mandate a minimum number of random bits for version 7; it allows the sub-millisecond precision and monotonicity counter fields to occupy the remainder of the 128-bit structure.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Consequently, collision resistance and guessability depend entirely on the specific implementation's allocation of these bits.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This is a "variant 0" NCS UUID with an address family of "0", defined in NCS as "unspecified or uninitialized".
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The Max UUID, sometimes also called the Omni UUID, is `FFFFFFFF-FFFF-FFFF-FFFF-FFFFFFFFFFFF` (that is, all set bits).
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This is intended to be used for expressing "end of UUID list".
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 incorporated legacy NCS UUIDs as "variant 0" of the new format by overlapping the variant bits of the new format with the NCS Address Family field.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Since the highest address family value defined in NCS is 13 (hex 00 to 0D), the most significant bit in the variant octet is always 0 for extant NCS UUIDs, while this bit is 1 in the newer three IETF variants.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In effect, NCS address families 0–127 became the new "variant 0", while the numbering space of NCS address families 128–255, which was undefined in NCS, was rededicated to variant-1-to-3 IETF and Microsoft UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The result was that legacy NCS UUIDs and variant-1-to-3 UUIDs were separated and could coexist in the same databases, and on the same communication channels.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The legacy Apollo NCS UUID has the format described in the previous table.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The OSF DCE UUID variant is described in RFC 9562.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The Microsoft COM / DCOM UUID has its variant described in the Microsoft documentation, but for versions 1 to 5, is generally the same as the DCE variant, except for the extra variant bit and byte-ordering.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] (See next section.) Variant 2 does not have versions 6 to 8.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The interpretation of the various bit-blocks varies in variants 1 and 2 according to the "version".
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In variant 2, data_a, data_b, version|data_c are byte-swapped and variant|data_d and data_e are not byte-swapped.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Variant 1 UUIDs are sequentially encoded in big-endian.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In contrast, variant 2 UUIDs ("GUIDs"): historically used in Microsoft COM/OLE libraries, have a mixed-endian format, with the first three fields (corresponding to version-1 timestamp subfields) being little-endian, while the final two fields are emitted as big-endian arrays of bytes.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The example UUID above, if it were a variant 2 UUID, would be encoded on the wire as `33 22 11 00 55 44 77 66 88 99 aa bb cc dd ee ff`.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] All versions under variant 2 are emitted with this byte ordering, including versions not containing numeric fields, such as 3,4, and 5.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In most cases, UUIDs are represented as hexadecimal values separated by hyphens.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Most used is the 8-4-4-4-12 format, a string of 32 hexadecimal digits with four hyphens, `xxxxxxxx-xxxx-vxxx-wxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx`.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The hyphens separate the version-1 fields but the same format is commonly used for all versions.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Every hexadecimal digit represents 4 bits; `v` represents the version nibble; and the high-order one to three bits of `w` are the variant.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The Windows registry format is the same but wraps the UUID in `{}` braces.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The byte-ordering differences of variant 2 are applicable in binary storage or transmission on the wire, and do not affect the textual presentation of the UUID.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Though they are still occasionally omitted, the format with hyphens was introduced with the newer variant system.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The first part is the time (time_high and time_low combined).
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The family field comes directly after the first dot, so in this case `0d` (13 in decimal) for DDS (Data Distribution Service).
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The remaining parts, each separated with a dot, are the node bytes.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Lowercase hexadecimal digits are preferred.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] X.667 requires lowercase on generation, but also requires the uppercase version to be accepted on input.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Since UUIDs are 128-bit numbers, other formats are possible, and occasionally seen, such as decimal digits or binary.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 registers the "uuid" namespace for URNs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The normal 8-4-4-4-12 format is used for this.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] It is also possible to make an OID out of a UUID, which in turn provides another way to make a URN from it.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The unsigned decimal form of the UUID is prefixed with `2.25`, which represents the `{joint-iso-itu-t(2) uuid(25)}` "arc" within the OID namespace.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This may be further prefixed with `urn:oid:` to make a second form of URN for UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In general, the `uuid` URN is recommended over the `oid` URN.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] A collision occurs when the same UUID is generated more than once and is assigned to different referents.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] In the case of many standard version-1, -2, or -6 UUIDs using unique MAC addresses and/or timestamps, collisions can occur only as a result of error, such as manufacturing problems, skewed clocks, or software bugs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Duplicate UUIDs can also occur due to error with the UUID versions generated using processes such as random number generation or hashing.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] It is important, for example, to have a high-entropy source of randomness when generating version-4 UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] But collisions can also occur without error with such UUIDs, due to chance -- "bad luck".
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The probability of this is normally so small that it can be ignored, and can be computed precisely based on analysis of the birthday problem.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This number would be equivalent to generating 1 billion UUIDs per second for about 86 years.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] A file containing this many UUIDs, at 16 bytes per UUID, would be about 43.4 exabytes (37.7 EiB) -- a file, listing only identifiers, a few orders of magnitude larger than the largest databases currently in existence, which are on the order of 100 PB (e.g.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] If generated according to the standards, duplicate UUIDs are more likely to be the result of bit-flips (a so called Single-event upset) caused by cosmic rays passing through memory or disk storage, than the result of mischance at UUID-generation time.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, the probability to find a duplicate within 103 trillion properly-generated version-4 UUIDs is one in a billion.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Several filesystem types (for example, ext4 and Btrfs) use a UUID to uniquely identify each filesystem to the operating system.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Filesystem userspace tools, most of which are derived from the original implementation by Theodore Ts'o, therefore make use of UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The GUID Partition Table (GPT) uses UUIDs (called there "GUID"s) to identify partitions and partition types.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Unique partition IDs are assigned locally by the operating system.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Partition type IDs are well-known numbers, usually assigned by operating-system or hardware vendors.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] UUIDs are commonly used as a unique key in database tables.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The NEWID function in Microsoft SQL Server version 4 Transact-SQL returns standard random version-4 UUIDs, while the NEWSEQUENTIALID function returns 128-bit identifiers similar to UUIDs which are committed to ascend in sequence until the next system reboot.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The Oracle Database SYS_GUID function does not return a standard GUID, despite the name.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] Instead, it returns a 16-byte 128-bit RAW value based on a host identifier and a process or thread identifier, somewhat similar to a GUID.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] PostgreSQL contains a UUID datatype and can generate most versions of UUIDs through the use of functions from modules.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] MySQL provides a UUID function which generates standard version-1 UUIDs.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] The random nature of standard UUIDs of versions 3, 4, and 5, and the ordering of the fields within standard versions 1 and 2 may create problems with database locality or performance when UUIDs are used as primary keys.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] For example, in 2002 Jimmy Nilsson reported a significant improvement in performance with Microsoft SQL Server when the version-4 UUIDs being used as keys were modified to include a non-random suffix based on system time.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] By reordering and encoding version-1 and -2 UUIDs so that the timestamp comes first, insertion performance loss can be averted.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] This is the rationale for variant 1 (DCE) versions 6 and 7, standardized in RFC 9562.
[src:idor-prevention/universally-unique-identifier] UEFI and ACPI are examples that use GUID.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In astronomy, geography and related sciences, a line or plane passing by a given point is said to be **vertical** if it contains the local gravity direction at that point.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Conversely, a line or plane is said to be **horizontal** (or *leveled*) if it is perpendicular to the vertical at a given point.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] By extension, the concept applies to finite objects contained by a line or a plane, such as line segments, plane regions, vectors, directions, etc.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] A surface is horizontal if its tangent planes are everywhere perpendicular to the gravity vector at the tangent point or, equivalently, if the surface normal vector is everywhere parallel to gravity, as in an equigeopotential surface.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] More generally, something that is *vertical* can be drawn from "up" to "down" (or down to up), such as the y-axis in the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] The word *horizontal* is derived from the Latin *horizon*, which derives from the Greek ὁρῐ́ζων, meaning 'separating' or 'marking a boundary'.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] The word *vertical* is derived from the late Latin **verticalis**, which is from the same root as *vertex*, meaning 'highest point' or more literally the 'turning point' such as in a whirlpool.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Girard Desargues defined the vertical to be perpendicular to the horizon in his 1636 book *Perspective*.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In physics, engineering and construction, the orientation designated as vertical is usually that along which a plumb-bob hangs.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Alternatively, a spirit level that exploits the buoyancy of an air bubble and its tendency to go vertically upwards may be used to test for horizontality.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] A water level device may also be used to establish horizontality.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Modern rotary laser levels that can level themselves automatically are robust sophisticated instruments and work on the same fundamental principle.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] When the curvature of the Earth is taken into account, the concepts of vertical and horizontal take on yet another meaning.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] On the surface of a smoothly spherical, homogenous, non-rotating planet, the plumb bob picks out as vertical the radial orientation.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Strictly speaking, it is now no longer possible for vertical walls to be parallel: *all* verticals intersect.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] This fact has real practical applications in construction and civil engineering, e.g., the tops of the towers of a suspension bridge are further apart than at the bottom.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Also, horizontal planes can intersect when they are tangent planes to separated points on the surface of the Earth.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In particular, a plane tangent to a point on the equator intersects the plane tangent to the North Pole at a right angle.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Furthermore, the equatorial plane is parallel to the tangent plane at the North Pole and as such has claim to be a horizontal plane.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] But it is. at the same time, a vertical plane for points on the equator.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In this sense, a plane can, arguably, be *both* horizontal and vertical, horizontal *at one place*, and vertical *at another*.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] For a spinning earth, the plumb line deviates from the radial orientation as a function of latitude.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Only on the equator and at the North and South Poles does the plumb line align with the local radius.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] The situation is actually even more complicated because Earth is not a homogeneous smooth sphere.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] It is a non homogeneous, non spherical, knobby planet in motion, and the vertical not only need not lie along a radial, it may even be curved and be varying with time.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] On a smaller scale, a mountain to one side may deflect the plumb bob away from the true zenith.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] On a larger scale the gravitational field of the Earth, which is at least approximately radial near the Earth, is not radial when it is affected by the Moon at higher altitudes.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Neglecting the curvature of the earth, horizontal and vertical motions of a projectile moving under gravity are independent of each other.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Vertical displacement of a projectile is not affected by the horizontal component of the launch velocity, and, conversely, the horizontal displacement is unaffected by the vertical component.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] The notion dates at least as far back as Galileo.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] When the curvature of the Earth is taken into account, the independence of the two motion does *not* hold.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] For example, even a projectile fired in a horizontal orientation (i.e., with a zero vertical component) may leave the surface of the spherical Earth and indeed escape altogether.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In the context of a 1-dimensional orthogonal Cartesian coordinate system on a Euclidean plane, to say that a line is horizontal or vertical, an initial designation has to be made.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] One can start off by designating the vertical orientation, usually labelled the Y orientation.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] The horizontal orientation, usually labelled the X orientation, is then automatically determined.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Or, one can do it the other way around, i.e., nominate the *x*-axis, in which case the *y*-axis is then automatically determined.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] There is no special reason to choose the horizontal over the vertical as the initial designation: the two orientation are on par in this respect.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] A *vertical line* is any line parallel to the vertical orientation.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] A *horizontal line* is any line normal to a vertical line.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Horizontal lines do not cross each other.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Not all of these elementary geometric facts are true in the 3-D context.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In the three-dimensional case, the situation is more complicated as now one has horizontal and vertical planes in addition to horizontal and vertical lines.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Consider a point P and designate a orientation through P as vertical.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] A plane which contains P and is normal to the designated orientation is the *horizontal plane* at P.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Any plane going through P, normal to the horizontal plane is a *vertical plane* at P.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Through any point P, there is one and only one horizontal plane but a *multiplicity* of vertical planes.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] This is a new feature that emerges in three dimensions.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] The symmetry that exists in the two-dimensional case no longer holds.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In the 2-dimension case, as mentioned already, the usual designation of the vertical coincides with the y-axis in co-ordinate geometry.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] This convention can cause confusion in the classroom.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] For the teacher, writing perhaps on a white board, the *y*-axis really is vertical in the sense of the plumbline verticality but for the student the axis may well lie on a horizontal table.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Although the word horizontal is commonly used in daily life and language (see below), it is subject to many misconceptions.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In general or in practice, something that is horizontal can be drawn from left to right (or right to left), such as the x-axis in the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] The concept of a horizontal plane is thus anything but simple, although, in practice, most of these effects and variations are rather small: they are measurable and can be predicted with great accuracy, but they may not greatly affect our daily life.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Hence, the world appears to be flat locally, and horizontal planes in nearby locations appear to be parallel.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] Such statements are nevertheless approximations; whether they are acceptable in any particular context or application depends on the applicable requirements, in particular in terms of accuracy.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In graphical contexts, such as drawing and drafting and Co-ordinate geometry on rectangular paper, it is very common to associate one of the dimensions of the paper with a horizontal, even though the entire sheet of paper is standing on a flat horizontal (or slanted) table.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] In this case, the horizontal orientation is typically from the left side of the paper to the right side.
[src:idor-prevention/vertical-and-horizontal] This is purely conventional (although it is somehow 'natural' when drawing a natural scene as it is seen in reality), and may lead to misunderstandings or misconceptions, especially in an educational context.
